04615nam a22007815i 9780823286492DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232864927 a10.1515/97808232864922doi  a(DE-B1597)555225  a(OCoLC)1122454072  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBJ1533.G4bH4613 2020 7aPHI0430002bisacsh04a177/.72231 aHénaff, Marcel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Philosophers' Gift :bReexamining Reciprocity /cMarcel Hénaff. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTranslator’s Preface -- tPreliminary Directions -- tChapter 1. Derrida: The Gift, the Impossible, and the Exclusion of Reciprocity -- tChapter 2. Propositions I: The Ceremonial Gift— Alliance and Recognition -- tChapter 3. Levinas: Beyond Reciprocity— For-the-Other and the Costly Gift -- tChapter 4. Propositions II: Approaches to Reciprocity -- tChapter 5. Marion: Gift without Exchange— Toward Pure Givenness -- tChapter 6. Ricoeur: Reciprocity and Mutuality— From the Golden Rule to Agape -- tChapter 7. Philosophy and Anthropology: With Lefort and Descombes -- tChapter 8. Propositions III: The Dual Relationship and the Third Party -- tPostliminary Directions -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWinner, French Voices Award for excellence in publication and translation.When it comes to giving, philosophers love to be the most generous. For them, every form of reciprocity is tainted by commercial exchange. In recent decades, such thinkers as Derrida, Levinas, Henry, Marion, Ricoeur, Lefort, and Descombes, have made the gift central to their work, haunted by the requirement of disinterestedness.As an anthropologist as well as a philosopher, Hénaff worries that philosophy has failed to distinguish among various types of giving. The Philosophers’ Gift returns to Mauss to reexamine these thinkers through the anthropological tradition. Reciprocity, rather than disinterestedness, he shows, is central to ceremonial giving and alliance, whereby the social bond specific to humans is proclaimed as a political bond. From the social fact of gift practices, Hénaff develops an original and profound theory of symbolism, the social, and the relationship between self and other, whether that other is an individual human being, the collective other of community and institution, or the impersonal other of the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGenerosityxPhilosophy. 0aGiftsxPhilosophy. 0aInterpersonal relationsxPhilosophy. 0aReciprocity (Psychology). 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Post-Structuralism.2bisacsh  aGift.  aalliance.  agivenness.  areciprocity.  asocial bond.  asymbolism.  athird party.1 aMorhange, Jean-Louis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311072273440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823286492zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823286492423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823286492/original  a978-3-11-072273-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK